{"type":"message","id":"9703eb92","parentId":"7a9b6929","timestamp":"2026-04-16T12:19:07.363Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"No output from the CDP endpoint. Maybe the Chrome debugging is on a different port or not accessible. Let me check the browser status again and see if I can start the user profile properly.Actually, let me step back. The user profile approach requires Chrome MCP auto-connect, which is more complex to set up. Let me check if the existing-session driver is working properly by looking at the browser status.\n\nActually, looking at the docs again, the `user` profile with `driver: \"existing-session\"` uses Chrome MCP auto-connect. The issue might be that:1. Chrome MCP needs to be running\n2. The Chrome needs to have remote debugging enabled on the default port\n\nLet me try a different approach - use CDP URL directly to connect to the user's Chrome if we know the debugging port.\n\nWait, actually the user sent a screenshot earlier showing Chrome remote debugging at `chrome://inspect/#remote-debugging` and it showed `127.0.0.1:9222`. But when I curl that port, there's no response. Maybe the debugging port is not accessible or Chrome closed that port.\n\nLet me try the CDP WebSocket connection to see if Chrome is listening.Actually, maybe I should just focus on making the current `openclaw` profile work well since that's already functioning. The user said \"可以了\" which might mean they're OK with continuing with the current setup.\n\nBut they specifically asked about whether we're using their Chrome or a separate instance. I confirmed it's a separate instance. They might want to switch to their Chrome.\n\nLet me try one more thing - check if we can access the CDP port:"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_ntilo03157je_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"curl -s --connect-timeout 3 http://127.0.0.1:9222/ 2>&1 || echo \"Connection failed\"","timeout":5}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"minimax"